    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-03-23T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-03-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="215"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d215">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 857.857/107</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at La Rochelle</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Goodier</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">La Rochelle</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date
                            ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-content-and-sibling-dates"
                            calendar="gregorian" when="1917-03-23">
                            <hi rend="italic">undated</hi>
                        </date>. <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received March 23, 1917,
                        midnight.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Norwegian steamship <hi rend="italic">Avra, en route</hi> Penarth, Wales, to
                    Blaye, France, with cargo of coal, sunk by submarine without warning on morning
                    of March 19. Nationality of submarine not definitely known, suspected German.
                    Two torpedoes fired, one striking bow, second amidships. Ship sank in about 30
                    minutes. Night cloudy. Long swell at sea. Crew took to lifeboats and were picked
                    up by Greek ship, conveyed to La Palice, France. Attack made 8 miles southeast
                    of Chassiron Light, He d’Oléron, about equal distance from coast of France. Crew
                    of 22; 17 landed, 4 drowned, 1 missing. One American, <persName>Thomas A.
                        Waters</persName> of 1306 Walnut Street, Philadelphia, <pb facs="0358"
                        n="186" xml:id="pg_186"/> Pa., on board at time, saved; Waters sustained
                    four wounds of minor importance. Full report and depositions follow by mail.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Goodier</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
